p:
The traditional south region of Minas Gerais may lose suitable areas for coffee growing over the years (
 Tavares et al., 2017; 
 Pinto et al., 2008; 
 Zullo et al., 2006; 
 Assad et al., 2004), especially due to temperature increase and modified rainfall pattern. Temperature is the most important and decisive meteorological variable to define suitable coffee areas (
 Rahn et al., 2014), interfering in the blossoming, fruit quality, and growth. Adaptation is therefore required and, since shade management reduces temperature, the practice may be considered a significant option to adapt coffee to climate change. However, as suggested in this study, the low level of shades may not reduce temperature in the blossoming period, but may reduce it along the year. Therefore, it is essential to plan shade schemes to reduce thermal stress.
